:0;list-style-type:decimal"><li><i>Another Fubo win</i>: The prospects of V=
enu launching anytime in 2025=E2=80=94or ever, really=E2=80=94took another =
blow last week when a federal judge denied motions by ESPN, Fox, and Warner=
 Bros. Discovery to dismiss Fubo=E2=80=99s antitrust case <i>and</i> move t=
he case to a different jurisdiction where it could have, potentially, wound=
 up in front of a friendlier judge. The decision essentially guarantees tha=
t there=E2=80=99s no escape hatch for the strange bedfellows who teamed up =
to create Venu and, frankly, already seem headed on disparate paths into th=
e cable dystopia less than one year later.<br/><br/>The appellate courts ar=
e going to be crucial here. And it=E2=80=99s important to note that while t=
he appeal continues, the companies will have to
deal with a discovery process that no executive wants to be <i>anywhere</i>=
 near. Meanwhile, in retrospect, the denial of the motion to dismiss hardly=
 came as a surprise. (After all, if that motion had any chance of happening=
, the injunction would not have been issued in the first place.) Fox=E2=80=
=99s push to switch jurisdictions seemed to have a better chance of succeed=
ing, since it was based on contract language with Fubo, but  Judge <b>Marga=
ret Garnett</b> swatted it aside. Not only did she suggest that Fox was try=
ing to judge-shop, but also that the company had waited too long to make it=
s objection.</li><br/><li><i>ESPN Flagship predictions</i>: MoffettNathanso=
n=E2=80=99s <b>Robert Fishman</b> published a note this morning suggesting =
that ESPN=E2=80=99s forthcoming =E2=80=9CFlagship=E2=80=9D streaming servic=
e may wind up being the goldilocks product offering that many are hoping fo=
r in Bristol. Indeed, like most businesses that find themselves in the maw =
of the innovator=E2=80=99s dilemma, ESPN is trying
to create a new product that secures its economic future without totally un=
dercutting its existing model. In this case, chairman <b>Jimmy Pitaro </b>(=
under the watchful eye of <b>Bob Iger</b>) has been trying to develop an of=
fering that will add incremental value, largely by attracting cord-cutters =
and cord-nevers, without totally delegitimizing the cable bundle.<br/><br/>=
Fishman predicts that Flagship will amass 1 million paid subscribers by the=
 end of 2026 and as many as 3 million by 2030, all paying around $25 a mont=
h, or $300 per year=E2=80=A6 at least at first. In particular, he estimated=
 the service would bring in $200 million-plus in subscriber revenue the yea=
r after next (remember, those 1 million subscribers will accumulate over th=
e course of 12 months) and around $20 million in advertising revenue. (This=
 last figure seems conservative, and the accounting is also pretty fungible=
=2E) Projecting these numbers out, the=20=
service could likely do well over a bi=
llion dollars in
annual revenue by the end of the decade=E2=80=94a nice number, but pretty s=
mall in the grand scheme of things, and less than the network pays for any =
of its major sports packages. (As a reminder, ESPN made $16 billion in 2022=
 and amassed about $2.9 billion in profit.) In the end, all this underscore=
s the complexities of Pitaro=E2=80=99s choreography: He desperately needs t=
o move ESPN toward the future, but he <i>cannot </i>yank the cord on cable =
too quickly. <br/><br/></li><li><i>On Kraft=E2=80=99s close relationship wi=
th Goodell</i>: <b>Seth Wickersham</b>, the great ESPN reporter, joins me o=
n Wednesday=E2=80=99s episode of the <i>Varsity</i> podcast to discuss Beli=
chick=E2=80=99s decision to coach in college next season. We also touch on =
the relationship between Patriots owner <b>Robert Kraft</b> and NFL commish=
 <b>Roger Goodell</b>, two secondary characters in the Belichick cinematic =
universe. Kraft and Goodell had always been close, dating back to the <b>Ta=
gliabue </b>era, and several other owners
resented the league=E2=80=99s handling of Spygate, which led to wrist-slapp=
ing fines and lost draft picks. Many suspected that Goodell overcompensated=
 for this, consciously or not, by suspending Brady four games in the wake o=
f Deflategate, resulting in <i>everyone</i> hating <i>everyone</i>.<br/><br=
/>For what it=E2=80=99s worth, Wickersham clarified that Kraft and Goodell =
were never on the outs. Instead, he reserved his ire for others. =E2=80=9CK=
raft was angry at the league office, but he really wasn=E2=80=99t with Good=
ell,=E2=80=9D Wickersham told me. =E2=80=9CPeople would be in the league of=
fice and watch Kraft outside of Roger Goodell=E2=80=99s office. When <b>Jef=
f Pash</b>, the general counsel whose office is nearby, would exit, Kraft w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t even look at Pash. But he=E2=80=99d keep talking with Goode=
ll.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Our conversation also touched on Kraft=E2=80=99s wani=
ng juice. =E2=80=9CAt this point, I=E2=80=99m not sure what Kraft=E2=80=99s=
 power is in league circles,=E2=80=9D Wickersham told me. =E2=80=9CYou alwa=
ys just kind of point to Kraft and
<b>Jerry Jones</b> as the two big guns in those circles. But I do think tha=
t as they age, their influence is waning a little.=E2=80=9D He continued: =
=E2=80=9CThere haven=E2=80=99t been a lot of contested issues in NFL circle=
s for a while. The media deals are done; the C.B.A. is done. One of the fun=
ny things about owners is that groupthink takes over quite a bit. Most of t=
hese votes are not really contested.=E2=80=9D Of course, both Kraft and Jon=
es have delegated a lot of work to their sons, <b>Jonathan </b>and <b>Steph=
en</b>, respectively.<br/><br/></li><li><i>Zaz=E2=80=99s P.E. playbook</i>:=
